[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] IEEE 802.1Qat and 802.1Qav amendments have been incorporated to the base IEEE 802.1Q-2011 document, which specifies the operation of Media Access Control (MAC) Bridges and Virtual Bridged Local Area Networks.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] AVB was initially developed by the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) Audio Video Bridging task group of the IEEE 802.1 standards committee.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] In November 2012, Audio Video Bridging task group was renamed to Time-Sensitive Networking task group to reflect the expanded scope of its work, which is to "provide the specifications that will allow time-synchronized low latency streaming services through IEEE 802 networks".
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] Further standardization efforts are ongoing in IEEE 802.1 TSN task group.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] To help ensure interoperability between devices that implement the AVB and TSN standards, the AVnu Alliance develops device certification for the automotive, consumer, and professional audio and video markets.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] Analog audio-video (AV) equipment historically used one-way, single-purpose, point-to-point connections.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] Even digital AV standards, such as S/PDIF for audio and the serial digital interface (SDI) for video, retain these properties.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] This connection model results in large masses of cables, especially in professional applications and high-end audio.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] Attempts to solve these problems were based on multi-point network topologies, such as IEEE 1394 (FireWire), and included adaptation of standard switched computer network technologies such as Audio over Ethernet and Audio over IP.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] Professional, home, and automotive AV solutions came to use specialized protocols that do not interoperate with each other or standard IT protocols, while standard computer networks did not provide tight quality of service with strict timing and predictable or bounded latency.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] To overcome these limitations, Audio Video Bridging networks transmit multiple audiovisual streams through standard Ethernet switches (i.e.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] *MAC bridges*) connected in a hierarchical tree topology.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] AVB includes layer 2 protocols to reserve connection bandwidth and prioritise network traffic, which guarantee precise sync clock and low transmission latency for each stream.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] Worst-case delay, including source and destination buffering, is required to be low and deterministic: the user-interface delay shall be around 50 ms, so that the pressing of a button and the resulting action are perceived as happening instantly, and 2 ms for live performance or studio work.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] Audio Video Bridging is implemented as a switched Ethernet network that works by reserving a fraction of the available Ethernet for AV traffic.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] The IEEE 802.1BA is an umbrella standard for these three principal technologies, which defines application-specific configurations and operation procedures for devices in switched audio-video networks.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] AVB traffic is replicated in a multicast manner, with one talker (stream initiator) and multiple listeners.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] AVB packets are sent at regular intervals in the allocated time slots, preventing collisions for AV traffic.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] AVB guarantees a latency of 2 ms for Class A traffic and 50 ms for Class B traffic over a maximum of 7 hops, with a transmission period of 125 μs for Class A and 250 μs for Class B traffic.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] An IEEE 802.1AS network timing domain includes all devices that communicate using the gPTP protocol.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] The grandmaster is a device chosen as the reference clock; the 802.1BA specification requires every talker and network bridge to be grandmaster capable.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] 802.3 link management and 802.1AS link delay measurement protocols calculate the round-trip delay to the AVB endpoint; this needs to be better than worst-case wire delay from the 802.1AS peer delay algorithm.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] Higher-level protocols may use 802.1AS clock information to set the exact presentation time for each AV stream.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] IEEE Std 1722-2011 for a Layer 2 Audio Video Transport Protocol (AVTP) defines details for transmitting IEEE 1394/IEC 61883 streams and other AV formats, setting the presentation time for each AV stream, and manage latencies from worst case delay calculated by the gPTP protocol.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] IEEE Std 1722.1-2013 is a standard that provides AVB discovery, enumeration, connection management, and control (AVDECC) of devices using IEEE Std 1722-2011.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] AVDECC defines operations to discover device addition and removal, retrieve device entity model, connect and disconnect streams, manage device and connection status, and remote control devices.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] Higher-layer services can improve synchronisation and latency of media transmission by mapping the AVB Stream ID to internal stream identifiers and basing internal timestamps on gPTP master clock.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] AES67 is based on standard RTP over UDP/IP and IEEE 1588 Precision Time Protocol (PTPv2) for timing; interoperability with AVB/TSN can be achieved by linking IEEE 802.1AS timing information to AES67 PTPv2 payload data.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] AES67 implementation with AVB interoperability has been demoed at InfoComm 2016.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] In 2018, the Avnu Alliance announced the Milan initiative to promote interoperability of AVB devices and provide product certification and testing.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] Redundancy is provided with two independent logical networks for every endpoint and a seamless switchover mechanism.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] The IETF Deterministic Networking (DetNet) Working Group is working to define deterministic data paths with bounds on latency, loss, and packet delay variation (jitter), and high reliability.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] DetNet shall operate over both Layer 2 bridged segments and Layer 3 routed segments, relying on interoperability with AVB/TSN switches when possible.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] The stated goal is to enable geographically distributed, campus- or enterprise-wide Intranet for content delivery with bounded low latency (10-15 ms).
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] A single network shall handle both A/V and IT traffic, with Layer 3 routing on top of AVB QoS networks to enable sharing content between Layer 2 AVB segments, and provide IntServ and DiffServ integration with AVB where possible.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] Unused reserved bandwidth shall be released for best-effort traffic.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] The protocol stack shall have Plug-and-play capabilities from top to bottom to reduce manual setup and administration, allow quick changes of network devices and network topology.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] The work on A/V streaming started at the IEEE 802.3re 'Residential Ethernet' study group in July 2004.
[src:audio-video-bridging/audio-video-bridging] In November 2005, it was moved to the IEEE 802.1 committee responsible for cross-network bridging standards.
[src:audio-video-bridging/ieee-802] The IEEE 802 LAN/MAN Standards Committee makes current standards freely available, after a six-month delay, through their Get IEEE 802.1 program.
[src:audio-video-bridging/ieee-802] Other recent 802.1 standards are available through the IEEE for a fee.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] In electronics and telecommunications, **jitter** is the deviation from true periodicity of a presumably periodic signal, often in relation to a reference clock signal.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] In clock recovery applications it is called **timing jitter**.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Jitter is a significant, and usually undesired, factor in the design of almost all communications links.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Jitter can be quantified in the same terms as all time-varying signals, e.g., root mean square (RMS), or peak-to-peak displacement.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Also, like other time-varying signals, jitter can be expressed in terms of spectral density.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Jitter may be caused by electromagnetic interference and crosstalk with carriers of other signals.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Jitter can cause a display monitor to flicker, affect the performance of processors in personal computers, introduce clicks or other undesired effects in audio signals, and cause loss of transmitted data between network devices.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] The amount of tolerable jitter depends on the affected application.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] in the position of a clock's edge from where it would ideally be.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Maximum error committed by a clock under test in measuring a time interval for a given period of time.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] The difference between any one clock period and the ideal or average clock period.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Hence, synchronous circuitry benefits from minimizing period jitter, so that the shortest clock period approaches the average clock period.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] The difference in duration of any two adjacent clock periods.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] In telecommunications, the unit used for the above types of jitter is usually the unit interval (UI) which quantifies the jitter in terms of a fraction of the transmission unit period.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] This unit is useful because it scales with clock frequency and thus allows relatively slow interconnects such as T1 to be compared to higher-speed internet backbone links such as OC-192.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Absolute units such as *picoseconds* are more common in microprocessor applications.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Units of *degrees* and *radians* are also used.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] If jitter has a Gaussian distribution, it is usually quantified using the standard deviation of this distribution.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] This translates to an RMS measurement for a zero-mean distribution.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Often, jitter distribution is significantly non-Gaussian.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] This can occur if the jitter is caused by external sources such as power supply noise.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] In these cases, *peak-to-peak* measurements may be more useful.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Many efforts have been made to meaningfully quantify distributions that are neither Gaussian nor have a meaningful peak level.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] All have shortcomings but most tend to be good enough for the purposes of engineering work.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] In computer networking, *jitter* can refer to packet delay variation, the variation (statistical dispersion) in the delay of the packets.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] One of the main differences between random and deterministic jitter is that deterministic jitter is bounded and random jitter is unbounded.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Random jitter, also called Gaussian jitter, is unpredictable electronic timing noise.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Random jitter typically follows a normal distribution due to being caused by thermal noise in an electrical circuit.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] in which the value of *n* is based on the BER required of the link.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] A common BER used in communication standards such as Ethernet is 10−12.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] In analog-to-digital and digital-to-analog conversion of signals, the sampling is normally assumed to be periodic with a fixed period—the time between every two samples is the same.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] If there is jitter present on the clock signal to the analog-to-digital converter or a digital-to-analog converter, the time between samples varies and instantaneous signal error arises.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] The error is proportional to the slew rate of the desired signal and the absolute value of the clock error.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] The effect of jitter on the signal depends on the nature of the jitter.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Random jitter tends to add broadband noise while deterministic jitter tends to add errant spectral components, *birdys*.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] In some conditions, less than a nanosecond of jitter can reduce the effective bit resolution of a converter with a Nyquist frequency of 22 kHz to 14 bits.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Sampling jitter is an important consideration in high-frequency signal conversion, or where the clock signal is especially prone to interference.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] In digital antenna arrays ADC and DAC jitters are the important factors determining the direction of arrival estimation accuracy and the depth of jammers suppression.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] In the context of computer networks, packet jitter or packet delay variation (PDV) is the variation in latency as measured in the variability over time of the end-to-end delay across a network.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] A network with constant delay has no packet jitter.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Packet jitter is expressed as an average of the deviation from the network mean delay.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] PDV is an important quality of service factor in assessment of network performance.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Transmitting a burst of traffic at a high rate followed by an interval or period of lower or zero rate transmission may also be seen as a form of jitter, as it represents a deviation from the average transmission rate.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] However, unlike the jitter caused by variation in latency, transmitting in bursts may be seen as a desirable feature, e.g. in variable bitrate transmissions.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Video or image jitter occurs when the horizontal lines of video image frames are randomly displaced due to the corruption of synchronization signals or electromagnetic interference during video transmission.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] A model-based dejittering study has been carried out under the framework of digital image and video restoration.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Jitter in serial bus architectures is measured by means of eye patterns.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] There are standards for jitter measurement in serial bus architectures.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] The standards cover jitter tolerance, jitter transfer function and jitter generation, with the required values for these attributes varying among different applications.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Where applicable, compliant systems are required to conform to these standards.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Testing for jitter and its measurement is of growing importance to electronics engineers because of increased clock frequencies in digital electronic circuitry to achieve higher device performance.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Higher clock frequencies have commensurately smaller eye openings and thus impose tighter tolerances on jitter.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] For example, modern computer motherboards have serial bus architectures with eye openings of 160 picoseconds or less.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] This is extremely small compared to parallel bus architectures with equivalent performance, which may have eye openings on the order of 1000 picoseconds.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Jitter is measured and evaluated in various ways depending on the type of circuit under test.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] In all cases, the goal of jitter measurement is to verify that the jitter will not disrupt normal operation of the circuit.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Testing of device performance for jitter tolerance may involve injection of jitter into electronic components with specialized test equipment.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] A less direct approach—in which analog waveforms are digitized and the resulting data stream analyzed—is employed when measuring pixel jitter in frame grabbers.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Anti-jitter circuits (AJCs) are a class of electronic circuits designed to reduce the level of jitter in a clock signal.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] AJCs operate by re-timing the output pulses so they align more closely to an idealized clock.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] They are widely used in clock and data recovery circuits in digital communications, as well as for data sampling systems such as the analog-to-digital converter and digital-to-analog converter.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Examples of anti-jitter circuits include phase-locked loop and delay-locked loop.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Jitter buffers or de-jitter buffers are buffers used to counter jitter introduced by queuing in packet-switched networks to ensure continuous playout of an audio or video media stream transmitted over the network.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] The maximum jitter that can be countered by a de-jitter buffer is equal to the buffering delay introduced before starting the play-out of the media stream.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] In the context of packet-switched networks, the term *packet delay variation* is often preferred over *jitter*.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Some systems use sophisticated delay-optimal de-jitter buffers that are capable of adapting the buffering delay to changing network characteristics.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] The adaptation logic is based on the jitter estimates computed from the arrival characteristics of the media packets.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Adjustments associated with adaptive de-jittering involve introducing discontinuities in the media play-out, which may be noticeable to the listener or viewer.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] Adaptive de-jittering is usually carried out for audio play-outs that include voice activity detection, which allows the lengths of the silence periods to be adjusted, thus minimizing the perceptual impact of the adaptation.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] A dejitterizer is a device that reduces jitter in a digital signal.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] A dejitterizer usually consists of an elastic buffer in which the signal is temporarily stored and then retransmitted at a rate based on the average rate of the incoming signal.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] A dejitterizer may not be effective in removing low-frequency jitter (wander).
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] A filter can be designed to minimize the effect of sampling jitter.
[src:audio-video-bridging/jitter] A jitter signal can be decomposed into intrinsic mode functions (IMFs), which can be further applied for filtering or dejittering.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] The **Precision Time Protocol** (**PTP**) is a protocol for clock synchronization throughout a computer network with relatively high precision as compared to using the earlier developed Network Time Protocol (NTP) and therefore *potentially* higher accuracy depending on the configuration.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] In a local area network (LAN), accuracy can be sub-microsecond – making it suitable for measurement and control systems applications.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] **IEEE 1588-2008**, also known as PTP Version 2, is not backward compatible with the 2002 version.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] **IEEE 1588-2019** was published in November 2019 and includes backward-compatible improvements to the 2008 publication.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] IEEE 1588-2008 includes a *profile* concept defining PTP operating parameters and options.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] Several profiles have been defined for applications including telecommunications, electric power distribution and audiovisual uses.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] **IEEE 802.1AS** is an adaptation of PTP, called gPTP, for use with Audio Video Bridging (AVB) and Time-Sensitive Networking (TSN).
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] According to John Eidson, who led the IEEE 1588-2002 standardization effort, "IEEE 1588 is designed to fill a niche not well served by either of the two dominant protocols, NTP and GPS.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] IEEE 1588 is designed for local systems requiring accuracies beyond those attainable using NTP.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] PTP was originally defined in the IEEE 1588-2002 standard, officially titled *Standard for a Precision Clock Synchronization Protocol for Networked Measurement and Control Systems*, and published in 2002.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] In 2008, IEEE 1588-2008 was released as a revised standard; also known as PTP version 2 (PTPv2), it improves accuracy, precision and robustness but is not backward compatible with the original 2002 version.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] IEEE 1588-2019 was published in November 2019, is informally known as *PTPv2.1* and includes backwards-compatible improvements to the 2008 publication.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] The IEEE 1588 standards describe a hierarchical master–slave architecture for clock distribution consisting of one or more network segments and one or more clocks.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] An *ordinary clock* is a device with a single network connection that is either the source of or the destination for a synchronization reference.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] A source is called a *master* (alternately *timeTransmitter*), and a destination is called a *slave* (alternately *timeReceiver*).
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] A *boundary clock* has multiple network connections and synchronizes one network segment to another.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] A single, synchronization leader is selected, a.k.a. elected, for each network segment.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] The root timing reference is called the *grandmaster*.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] A relatively simple PTP architecture consists of ordinary clocks on a single-segment network with no boundary clocks.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] A grandmaster is elected and all other clocks synchronize to it.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] IEEE 1588-2008 introduces a clock associated with network equipment used to convey PTP messages.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] The *transparent clock* modifies PTP messages as they pass through the device.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] Timestamps in the messages are corrected for time spent traversing the network equipment.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] This scheme improves distribution accuracy by compensating for delivery variability across the network.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] PTP typically uses the same epoch as Unix time (start of 1 January 1970).
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] While the Unix time is based on Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) and is subject to leap seconds, PTP is based on International Atomic Time (TAI).
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] The PTP grandmaster communicates the current offset between UTC and TAI, so that UTC can be computed from the received PTP time.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] Synchronization and management of a PTP system is achieved through the exchange of messages across the communications medium.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] To this end, PTP uses the following message types.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] Messages are categorized as *event* and *general* messages.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] *Event* messages are time-critical in that accuracy in transmission and receipt timestamp accuracy directly affects clock distribution accuracy.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] *Sync*, *Delay_Req*, *Pdelay_Req* and *Pdelay_resp* are *event* messages.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] *General* messages are more conventional protocol data units in that the data in these messages is of importance to PTP, but their transmission and receipt timestamps are not.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] *Announce*, *Follow_Up*, *Delay_Resp*, *Pdelay_Resp_Follow_Up*, *Management* and *Signaling* messages are members of the *general* message class.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] PTP messages may use the User Datagram Protocol over Internet Protocol (UDP/IP) for transport.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] IEEE 1588-2002 uses only IPv4 transports, but this has been extended to include IPv6 in IEEE 1588-2008.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] In IEEE 1588-2002, all PTP messages are sent using multicast messaging, while IEEE 1588-2008 introduced an option for devices to negotiate unicast transmission on a port-by-port basis.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] Multicast transmissions use IP multicast addressing, for which multicast group addresses are defined for IPv4 and IPv6 (see table).
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] Time-critical *event* messages (Sync, Delay_req, Pdelay_Req and Pdelay_Resp) are sent to port number 319.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] *General* messages (Announce, Follow_Up, Delay_Resp, Pdelay_Resp_Follow_Up, management and signaling) use port number 320.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] In IEEE 1588-2008, encapsulation is also defined for DeviceNet, ControlNet and PROFINET.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] A domain is an interacting set of clocks that synchronize to one another using PTP.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] Clocks are assigned to a domain by virtue of the contents of the *Subdomain name* (IEEE 1588-2002) or the *domainNumber* (IEEE 1588-2008) fields in PTP messages they receive or generate.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] Domains allow multiple clock distribution systems to share the same communications medium.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] Class – each clock is a member of a given class, each class getting its own priority.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] Priority 2 – final-defined priority, defining backup order in case the other criteria were not sufficient.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] Smaller numeric values indicate higher priority.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] Unique identifier – MAC address-based selection is used as a tiebreaker when all other properties are equal.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] IEEE 1588-2002 uses a selection algorithm based on similar properties.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] Clock properties are advertised in IEEE 1588-2002 *Sync* messages and in IEEE 1588-2008 *Announce* messages.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] The current leader transmits this information at regular interval.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] A clock that considers itself a better leader will transmit this information in order to invoke a change of leader.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] Once the current leader recognizes the better clock, the current leader stops transmitting *Sync* messages and associated clock properties (*Announce* messages in the case of IEEE 1588-2008) and the better clock takes over as leader.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] The BMCA only considers the self-declared quality of clocks and does not take network link quality into consideration.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] Via BMCA, PTP selects a source of time for an IEEE 1588 domain and for each network segment in the domain.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] Clocks determine the offset between themselves and their leader.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] Let the variable t represent physical time.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] where $s(t)$ represents the time measured by the follower clock at physical time t , and $m(t)$ represents the time measured by the leader clock at physical time t .
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] The leader periodically broadcasts the current time as a message to the other clocks.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] Under IEEE 1588-2002 broadcasts are up to once per second.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] Under IEEE 1588-2008, up to 10 per second are permitted.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] Each broadcast begins at time $T_{1}$ with a *Sync* message sent by the leader to all the clocks in the domain.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] A clock receiving this message takes note of the local time $T_{1}'$ when this message is received.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] The leader may subsequently send a multicast *Follow_Up* with accurate $T_{1}$ timestamp.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] Not all leaders have the ability to present an accurate timestamp in the *Sync* message.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] It is only after the transmission is complete that they are able to retrieve an accurate timestamp for the *Sync* transmission from their network hardware.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] Leaders with this limitation use the *Follow_Up* message to convey $T_{1}$ .
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] Leaders with PTP capabilities built into their network hardware are able to present an accurate timestamp in the *Sync* message and do not need to send Follow_Up messages.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] In order to accurately synchronize to their leader, clocks must individually determine the network transit time of the *Sync* messages.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] The transit time is determined indirectly by measuring round-trip time from each clock to its leader.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] The clocks initiate an exchange with their leader designed to measure the transit time d .
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] The exchange begins with a clock sending a *Delay_Req* message at time $T_{2}$ to the leader.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] The leader receives and timestamps the *Delay_Req* at time $T_{2}'$ and responds with a *Delay_Resp* message.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] The leader includes the timestamp $T_{2}'$ in the *Delay_Resp* message.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] The clock now knows the offset ${\tilde {o}}$ during this transaction and can correct itself by this amount to bring it into agreement with their leader.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] One assumption is that this exchange of messages happens over a period of time so small that this offset can safely be considered constant over that period.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] Another assumption is that the transit time of a message going from the leader to a follower is equal to the transit time of a message going from the follower to the leader.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] Finally, it is assumed that both the leader and follower can accurately measure the time they send or receive a message.
[src:audio-video-bridging/precision-time-protocol] The degree to which these assumptions hold true determines the accuracy of the clock at the follower device.
[src:audio-video-bridging/stream-reservation-protocol] SRP is part of the IEEE Audio Video Bridging (AVB) and Time-Sensitive Networking (TSN) standards.
[src:audio-video-bridging/stream-reservation-protocol] The SRP technical group started work in September 2006 and finished meetings in 2009.
[src:audio-video-bridging/stream-reservation-protocol] SRP registers a stream and reserves the resources required through the entire path taken by the stream, based on the bandwidth requirement and the latency which are defined by a stream reservation traffic class.
[src:audio-video-bridging/stream-reservation-protocol] Required bandwidth is calculated as MaxFrameSize × MaxIntervalFrames.
[src:audio-video-bridging/stream-reservation-protocol] If a bridge is able to reserve the required resources, it propagates the advertisement to the next bridge; otherwise a 'talker failed' message is raised.
[src:audio-video-bridging/stream-reservation-protocol] When the advertise message reaches the listener, it replies with 'listener ready' message that propagates back to the talker.
[src:audio-video-bridging/stream-reservation-protocol] Talker advertise and listener ready messages can be de-registered, which terminates the stream.
[src:audio-video-bridging/stream-reservation-protocol] Periodic polling of advertise and ready messages is used to detect unresponsive devices.
[src:audio-video-bridging/stream-reservation-protocol] Worst case latency is recalculated at every bridge, so higher protocol layers can use it for media synchronization.
[src:audio-video-bridging/stream-reservation-protocol] The per-port peer delay provided by gPTP and the network bridge residence delay are added to calculate the accumulated delays and ensure the latency requirement is met.
[src:audio-video-bridging/stream-reservation-protocol] Control traffic has the third highest priority and includes gPTP and SRP traffic.
[src:audio-video-bridging/stream-reservation-protocol] The SRP works using the Multiple MAC Registration Protocol (MMRP), the Multiple VLAN Registration Protocol (MVRP), and the Multiple Stream Registration Protocol (MSRP).
[src:audio-video-bridging/stream-reservation-protocol] MMRP controls propagation of group registration, and MVRP controls VLAN membership (MAC address information).
[src:audio-video-bridging/stream-reservation-protocol] MSRP works in a distributed network of bridges and end stations; it registers and advertises data streams and reserves bridge resources to provide the QoS guarantees.
[src:audio-video-bridging/stream-reservation-protocol] A station (talker) sends a reservation request with the general MRP application.
[src:audio-video-bridging/stream-reservation-protocol] All participants in the stream have an MSRP application and the MRP Attribute Declaration (MAD) specification for describing the stream characteristics.
[src:audio-video-bridging/stream-reservation-protocol] Then each bridge within the same SRP domain can map, allocate, and forward the stream with the necessary resources by using the MRP attribute propagation.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The majority of projects define extensions to the IEEE 802.1Q – Bridges and Bridged Networks, which describes virtual LANs and network switches.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] These extensions in particular address transmission with very low latency and high availability.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Applications include converged networks with real-time audio/video streaming and real-time control streams which are used in automotive applications and industrial control facilities.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Standard information technology network equipment has no concept of "time" and cannot provide synchronization and precision timing.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Delivering data reliably is more important than delivering within a specific time, so there are no constraints on delay or synchronization precision.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Even if the average hop delay is very low, individual delays can be unacceptably high.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Network congestion is handled by throttling and retransmitting dropped packets at the transport layer, but there are no means to prevent congestion at the link layer.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Data can be lost when the buffers are too small or the bandwidth is insufficient, but excessive buffering adds to the delay, which is unacceptable when low deterministic delays are required.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The different AVB/TSN standards documents specified by IEEE 802.1 can be grouped into three basic key component categories that are required for a complete real-time communication solution based on switched Ethernet networks with deterministic quality of service (QoS) for point-to-point connections.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Each and every standard specification can be used on its own and is mostly self-sufficient.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] However, only when used together in a concerted way, can TSN achieve its full potential as a communication system.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The IEEE AVB/TSN suite serves as the foundation for deterministic networking to satisfy the common requirements of these applications.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] AVB/TSN can handle rate-constrained traffic, where each stream has a bandwidth limit defined by minimum inter-frame intervals and maximal frame size, and time-trigger traffic with an exact accurate time to be sent.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Low-priority traffic is passed on a best-effort basis, with no timing and delivery guarantees.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] In contrast to standard Ethernet according to IEEE 802.3 and Ethernet bridging according to IEEE 802.1Q, time is very important in TSN networks.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] For real-time communication with hard, non-negotiable time boundaries for end-to-end transmission latencies, all devices in this network need to have a common time reference and therefore, need to synchronize their clocks among each other.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] This is not only true for the end devices of a communication stream, such as an industrial controller and a manufacturing robot, but also true for network components, such as Ethernet switches.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Only through synchronized clocks is it possible for all network devices to operate in unison and execute the required operation at exactly the required point in time.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Although time synchronization in TSN networks can be achieved with GPS clock, this is costly and there is no guarantee that the endpoint device has access to the radio or satellite signal at all times.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Due to these constraints, time in TSN networks is usually distributed from one central time source directly through the network itself using the IEEE 1588 Precision Time Protocol, which utilizes Ethernet frames to distribute time synchronization information.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1AS is a tightly constrained subset of IEEE 1588 with sub-microsecond precision and extensions to support synchronisation over WiFi radio (IEEE 802.11).
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The idea behind this profile is to narrow the huge list of different IEEE 1588 options down to a manageable few critical options that are applicable to home networks or networks in automotive or industrial automation environments.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1AS-2011 defines the Generalized Precision Time Protocol (gPTP) profile which, like all profiles of IEEE 1588, selects among the options of 1588, but also generalizes the architecture to allow PTP to apply beyond wired Ethernet networks.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] These calculated delays are then referenced to the GrandMaster (GM) clock in a bridge elected by the Best Master Clock Algorithm, a clock Spanning Tree Protocol to which all Clock Master (CM) and endpoint devices attempt to synchronize.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Any device that does not synchronize to timing messages is outside of the timing domain boundaries (Figure 2).
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Synchronization accuracy depends on precise measurements of link delay and frame residence time.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] 802.1AS uses *logical syntonization*, where a ratio between local clock and GM clock frequencies is used to calculate synchronized time, and a ratio between local and GM clock frequencies to calculate propagation delay.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE802.1AS-2020 introduces improved time measurement accuracy and support for multiple time domains for redundancy.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Scheduling and traffic shaping allow for the coexistence of different traffic classes with different priorities on the same network – each with different requirements for available bandwidth and end-to-end latency.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Traffic shaping refers to the process of distributing frames/packets evenly in time to smooth out the traffic.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Without traffic shaping at sources and bridges, the packets will *bunch*, i.e., agglomerate into bursts of traffic, overwhelming the buffers in subsequent bridges/switches along the path.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Standard bridging according to IEEE 802.1Q uses a strict priority scheme with eight distinct priorities.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] On the protocol level, these priorities are visible in the Priority Code Point (PCP) field in the 802.1Q VLAN tag of a standard Ethernet frame.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] These priorities already distinguish between more important and less important network traffic, but even with the highest of the eight priorities, no absolute guarantee for an end-to-end delivery time can be given.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The reason for this is buffering effects inside the Ethernet switches.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] If a switch has started the transmission of an Ethernet frame on one of its ports, even the highest-priority frame has to wait inside the switch buffer for this transmission to finish.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] With standard Ethernet switching, this nondeterminism cannot be avoided.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] This is not an issue in environments where applications do not depend on the timely delivery of single Ethernet frames - such as office IT infrastructures.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] In these environments, file transfers, emails or other business applications have limited time sensitivity themselves and are usually protected by other mechanisms further up the protocol stack, such as the Transmission Control Protocol.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] In industrial automation (Programmable Logic Controller (PLC) with an industrial robot) and automotive car environments, where closed loop control or safety applications are using the Ethernet network, reliable and timely delivery is of utmost importance.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] AVB/TSN enhances standard Ethernet communication by adding mechanisms to provide different time slices for different traffic classes and ensure timely delivery with soft and hard real-time requirements of control system applications.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The mechanism of utilizing the eight distinct VLAN priorities is retained, to ensure complete backward compatibility to non-TSN Ethernet.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Time-sensitive traffic has several priority classes.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] For credit-based shaper 802.1Qav, Stream Reservation Class A is the highest priority with a transmission period of 125 μs; Class B has the second-highest priority with a maximum transmission period of 250 μs.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Traffic classes shall not exceed their preconfigured maximum bandwidth (75% for audio and video applications).
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The worst-case latency requirement is defined as 2 ms for Class A and 50 ms for Class B, but has been shown to be unreliable.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Control traffic has the third-highest priority and includes gPTP and SRP traffic.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Time-aware scheduler 802.1Qbv introduces Class CDT for real-time control data from sensors and command streams to actuators, with worst-case latency of 100 μs over 5 hops, and a maximum transmission period of 0.5 ms.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Class CDT takes the highest priority over classes A, B, and control traffic.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1Qav Forwarding and Queuing Enhancements for Time-Sensitive Streams defines traffic shaping using priority classes, which is based on a simple form of leaky bucket credit-based fair queuing.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] 802.1Qav is designed to reduce buffering in receiving bridges and endpoints.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The credit-based shaper defines credits in bits for two separate queues, dedicated to Class A and Class B traffic.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Thus the idleSlope is the bandwidth reserved for the queue by the bridge, and the sendSlope is the transmission rate of the port MAC service.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] If the credit is negative and no frames are transmitted, credit increases at *idleSlope* rate until zero is reached.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] If an AVB frame cannot be transmitted because a non-AVB frame is in transmission, credit accumulates at *idleSlope* rate, but positive credit is allowed.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Additional limits hiCredit and loCredit are derived from the maximum frame size and maximum interference size, the idleSlope/sendSlope, and the maximum port transmission rate.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Reserved AV stream traffic frames are forwarded with high priority over non-reserved best-effort traffic, subject to credit-based traffic shaping rules which may require them to wait for a certain amount of credits.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] This protects best-effort traffic by limiting the maximum AV stream burst.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The frames are scheduled very evenly, though only on an aggregate basis, to smooth out the delivery times and reduce bursting and bunching, which can lead to buffer overflows and packet drops that trigger retransmissions.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The increased buffering delay makes re-transmitted packets obsolete by the time they arrive, resulting in frame drops, which reduces the quality of AV applications.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Deriving guaranteed upper bounds on delays in TSN is non-trivial and is currently being researched, e.g., by using the mathematical framework Network Calculus.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1Qat Stream Reservation Protocol (SRP) is a distributed peer-to-peer protocol that specifies admission controls based on resource requirements of the flow and available network resources.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] SRP reserves resources and advertises streams from the sender/source (talker) to the receivers/destinations (listeners); it works to satisfy QoS requirements for each stream and guarantee the availability of sufficient network resources along the entire flow transmission path.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The traffic streams are identified and registered with a 64-bit *StreamID*, made up of the 48-bit MAC address (EUI) and 16-bit *UniqueID* to identify different streams from the same source.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] SRP employs variants of Multiple Registration Protocol (MRP) to register and de-register attribute values on switches/bridges/devices - the Multiple MAC Registration Protocol (MMRP), the Multiple VLAN Registration Protocol (MVRP), and the Multiple Stream Registration Protocol (MSRP).
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Resources are allocated and configured in both the end nodes of the data stream and the transit nodes along the data flow path, with an end-to-end signaling mechanism to detect the success/failure.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Worst-case latency is calculated by querying every bridge.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Reservation requests use the general MRP application with the MRP attribute propagation mechanism.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] All nodes along the flow path pass the MRP Attribute Declaration (MAD) specification, which describes the stream characteristics so that bridges could allocate the necessary resources.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] If a bridge is able to reserve the required resources, it propagates the advertisement to the next bridge; otherwise, a *talker failed* message is raised.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] When the advertisement message reaches the listener, it replies with *listener ready* message that propagates back to the talker.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Successful reservation is only guaranteed when all intermediate nodes support SRP and respond to advertise and ready messages; in Figure 2 above, AVB domain 1 is unable to connect with AVB domain 2.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] SRP uses a decentralized registration and reservation procedure; multiple requests can introduce delays for critical traffic.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1Qcc-2018 "Stream Reservation Protocol (SRP) Enhancements and Performance Improvements" amendment reduces the size of reservation messages and redefines timers so they trigger updates only when link state or reservation is changed.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] CNC implements a per-stream request-response model, where SR class is not explicitly used: end-stations send requests for a specific stream (via edge port) without knowledge of the network configuration, and CNC performs stream reservation centrally.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] MSRP only runs on the link to end-stations as an information carrier between CNC and end-stations, not for stream reservation.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Centralized User Configuration (CUC) is an optional node that discovers end stations, their capabilities and user requirements, and configures delay-optimized TSN features (for closed-loop IACS applications).
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Seamless interop with Resource Reservation Protocol (RSVP) transport is provided.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] 802.1Qcc allows centralized configuration management to coexist with decentralized, fully distributed configuration of the SRP protocol, and also supports hybrid configurations for legacy AVB devices.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] 802.1Qcc can be combined with IEEE 802.1Qca Path Control and Reservation (PCR) and TSN traffic shapers.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] While the 802.1Qav FQTSS/CBS works very well with soft real-time traffic, worst-case delays are both hop count and network topology dependent.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Pathological topologies introduce delays, so buffer size requirements have to consider network topology.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] CQF can be used with the IEEE 802.1Qbv time-aware scheduler, IEEE 802.1Qbu frame preemption, and IEEE 802.1Qci ingress traffic policing.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1Qci Per-Stream Filtering and Policing (PSFP) improves network robustness by filtering individual traffic streams.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] It prevents traffic overload conditions that may affect bridges and the receiving endpoints due to malfunction or Denial of Service (DoS) attacks.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The stream filter uses rule matching to allow frames with specified stream IDs and priority levels and apply policy actions otherwise.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] All streams are coordinated at their gates, similarly to the 802.1Qch signaling.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The flow metering applies predefined bandwidth profiles for each stream.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The IEEE 802.1Qbv time-aware scheduler is designed to separate the communication on the Ethernet network into fixed length, repeating time cycles.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Within these cycles, different time slices can be configured that can be assigned to one or several of the eight Ethernet priorities.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] By doing this, it is possible to grant exclusive use - for a limited time - to the Ethernet transmission medium for those traffic classes that need transmission guarantees and can't be interrupted.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The basic concept is a time-division multiple access (TDMA) scheme.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] By establishing virtual communication channels for specific time periods, time-critical communication can be separated from non-critical background traffic.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Time-aware scheduler introduces Stream Reservation Class CDT for time-critical control data, with worst-case latency of 100 μs over 5 hops, and maximum transmission period of 0.5 ms, in addition to classes A and B defined for IEEE 802.1Qav credit-based traffic shaper.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] By granting exclusive access to the transmission medium and devices to time-critical traffic classes, the buffering effects in the Ethernet switch transmission buffers can be avoided and time-critical traffic can be transmitted without non-deterministic interruptions.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] In this example, each cycle consists of two time slices.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Time slice 1 only allows the transmission of traffic tagged with VLAN priority 3, and time slice 2 in each cycle allows for the rest of the priorities to be sent.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Since the IEEE 802.1Qbv scheduler requires all clocks on all network devices (Ethernet switches and end devices) to be synchronized and the identical schedule to be configured, all devices understand which priority can be sent to the network at any given point in time.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Since time slice 2 has more than one priority assigned to it, within this time slice, the priorities are handled according to standard IEEE 802.1Q strict priority scheduling.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] This separation of Ethernet transmissions into cycles and time slices can be enhanced further by the inclusion of other scheduling or traffic shaping algorithms, such as the IEEE 802.1Qav credit-based traffic shaper.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] In this particular example, IEEE 802.1Qav could be assigned to one or two of the priorities that are used in time slice two to distinguish further between audio/video traffic and background file transfers.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The Time-Sensitive Networking Task Group specifies a number of different schedulers and traffic shapers that can be combined to achieve the nonreactive coexistence of hard real-time, soft real-time and background traffic on the same Ethernet infrastructure.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] When an Ethernet interface has started the transmission of a frame to the transmission medium, this transmission has to be completely finished before another transmission can take place.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] This includes the transmission of the CRC-32 checksum at the end of the frame to ensure a reliable, fault-free transmission.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] This inherent property of Ethernet networks - again- poses a challenge to the TDMA approach of the IEEE 802.1Qbv scheduler.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Just before the end of time slice 2 in cycle n, a new frame transmission is started.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Unfortunately, this frame is too large to fit into its time slice.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Since the transmission of this frame cannot be interrupted, the frame infringes the following time slice 1 of the next cycle n+1.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] By partially or completely blocking a time-critical time slice, real-time frames can be delayed up to the point where they cannot meet the application requirements any longer.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] This is very similar to the actual buffering effects that happen in non-TSN Ethernet switches, so TSN has to specify a mechanism to prevent this from happening.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The IEEE 802.1Qbv time-aware scheduler has to ensure that the Ethernet interface is not busy with the transmission of a frame when the scheduler changes from one time slice to the next.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The time-aware scheduler achieves this by putting a guard band in front of every time slice that carries time-critical traffic.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] During this guard band time, no new Ethernet frame transmission may be started; only already ongoing transmissions may be finished.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The duration of this guard band has to be as long as it takes the maximum frame size to be safely transmitted.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The total time needed for sending this frame is dependent on the link speed of the Ethernet network.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] In this case, the guard band has to be at least 123.36 μs long.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] With the guard band, the total bandwidth or time that is usable within a time slice is reduced by the length of the guard band.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Note: to facilitate the presentation of the topic, the actual size of the guard band in figure 3 is not to scale, but is significantly smaller than indicated by the frame in figure 2.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] In this example, the time slice 1 always contains high-priority data (e.g. for motion control), while time slice 2 always contains best-effort data.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Therefore, a guard band needs to be placed at every transition point into time slice 1 to protect the time slice of the critical data stream(s).
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] To partially mitigate the loss of bandwidth through the guard band, the standard IEEE 802.1Qbv includes a length-aware scheduling mechanism.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] This mechanism is used when store-and-forward switching is utilized: after the full reception of an Ethernet frame that needs to be transmitted on a port where the guard band is in effect, the scheduler checks the overall length of the frame.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] If the frame can fit completely inside the guard band, without any infringement of the following high-priority slice, the scheduler can send this frame, despite an active guard band, and reduce the waste of bandwidth.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] This mechanism, however, cannot be used when cut-through switching is enabled, since the total length of the Ethernet frame needs to be known a priori.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Therefore, when cut-through switching is used to minimize end-to-end latency, the waste of bandwidth will still occur.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Also, this does not help with the minimum achievable cycle time.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Therefore, length-aware scheduling is an improvement, but cannot mitigate all drawbacks that are introduced by the guard band.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] To further mitigate the negative effects of the guard bands, the IEEE working groups 802.1 and 802.3 have specified the frame pre-emption technology.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The two working groups collaborated in this endeavour since the technology required both changes in the Ethernet Media Access Control (MAC) scheme that is under the control of IEEE 802.3, as well as changes in the management mechanisms that are under the control of IEEE 802.1.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Due to this fact, frame pre-emption is described in two different standards documents: IEEE 802.1Qbu for the bridge management component and IEEE 802.3br for the Ethernet MAC component.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Frame preemption defines two MAC services for an egress port: preemptable MAC (pMAC) and express MAC (eMAC).
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Express frames can interrupt the transmission of preemptable frames.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] On resume, MAC merge sublayer reassembles frame fragments in the next bridge.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Preemption causes computational overhead in the link interface, as the operational context shall be transitioned to the express frame.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Figure 4 gives a basic example how frame pre-emption works.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] During the process of sending a best effort Ethernet frame, the MAC interrupts the frame transmission just before the start of the guard band.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The partial frame is completed with a CRC and will be stored in the next switch to wait for the second part of the frame to arrive.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] After the high-priority traffic in time slice 1 has passed and the cycle switches back to time slice 2, the interrupted frame transmission is resumed.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Frame pre-emption always operates on a pure link-by-link basis and only fragments from one Ethernet switch to the next Ethernet switch, where the frame is reassembled.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] In contrast to fragmentation with the Internet Protocol (IP), no end-to-end fragmentation is supported.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Each partial frame is completed by a CRC-32 for error detection.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] In contrast to the regular Ethernet CRC-32, the last 16 bits are inverted to make a partial frame distinguishable from a regular Ethernet frame.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] In addition, the start of frame delimiter (SFD) is changed.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The support for frame pre-emption has to be activated on each link between devices individually.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] To signal the capability for frame pre-emption on a link, an Ethernet switch announces this capability through the LLDP (Link Layer Discovery Protocol).
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] When a device receives such an LLDP announcement on a network port and supports frame pre-emption itself, it may activate the capability.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] There is no direct negotiation and activation of the capability on adjacent devices.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Any device that receives the LLDP pre-emption announcement assumes that on the other end of the link, a device is present that can understand the changes in the frame format (changed CRC-32 and SFD).
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Frame pre-emption allows for a significant reduction of the guard band.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The length of the guard band is now dependent on the precision of the frame pre-emption mechanism: how small is the minimum size of the frame that the mechanism can still preempt.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.3br specifies the best accuracy for this mechanism at 64 bytes – due to the fact that this is the minimum size of a still valid Ethernet frame.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] In this case, the guard band can be reduced to a total of 127 bytes: 64 bytes (minimum frame) + 63 bytes (remaining length that cannot be pre-empted).
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] All larger frames can be pre-empted again and therefore, there is no need to protect against this size with a guard band.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] This minimizes the best effort bandwidth that is lost and also allows for much shorter cycle times at slower Ethernet speeds, such as 100 Mbit/s and below.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Since the pre-emption takes place in hardware in the MAC, as the frame passes through, cut-through switching can be supported as well, since the overall frame size is not needed a priori.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The MAC interface just checks in regular 64-byte intervals whether the frame needs to be preempted or not.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The combination of time synchronization, the IEEE 802.1Qbv scheduler and frame pre-emption already constitutes an effective set of standards that can be utilized to guarantee the coexistence of different traffic categories on a network while also providing end-to-end latency guarantees.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] This will be enhanced further as new IEEE 802.1 specifications, such as 802.1Qch are finalized.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Overall, the time-aware scheduler has high implementation complexity and its use of bandwidth is not efficient.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Task and event scheduling in endpoints has to be coupled with the gate scheduling of the traffic shaper in order to lower the latencies.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] A critical shortcoming is that some delay is incurred when an endpoint streams unsynchronized data, due to the waiting time for the next time-triggered window.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The time-aware scheduler requires tight synchronization of its time-triggered windows, so all bridges on the stream path must be synchronized.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] However, synchronizing TSN bridge frame selection and transmission time is nontrivial even in moderately sized networks and requires a fully managed solution.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Frame preemption is hard to implement and has not seen wide industry support.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Credit-based, time-aware and cyclic (peristaltic) shapers require network-wide coordinated time and utilize network bandwidth inefficiently, as they enforce packet transmission at periodic cycles.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The IEEE 802.1Qcr Asynchronous Traffic Shaper (ATS) operates asynchronously based on local clocks in each bridge, improving link utilization for mixed traffic types, such as periodic with arbitrary periods, sporadic (event driven), and rate-constrained.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] ATS employs the urgency-based scheduler (UBS), which prioritizes urgent traffic using per-class queuing and per-stream reshaping.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Asynchronicity is achieved by interleaved shaping with traffic characterization based on Token Bucket Emulation, a token bucket emulation model, to eliminate the burstiness cascade effects of per-class shaping.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The TBE shaper controls the traffic by average transmission rate, but allows a certain level of burst traffic.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] When there is a sufficient number of tokens in the bucket, transmission starts immediately; otherwise, the queue's gate closes for the time needed to accumulate enough tokens.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] This separation of queuing has low implementation complexity while ensuring that frames with higher priority will bypass the lower priority frames.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The shared queues are highly isolated, with policies for separate queues for frames from different transmitters, the same transmitter but different priority, and the same transmitter and priority but a different priority at the receiver.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Queue isolation prevents propagation of malicious data, assuring that ordinary streams will get no interference, and enables flexible stream or transmitter blocking by administrative action.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The minimum number of shared queues is the number of ports minus one, and more with additional isolation policies.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Shared queues have scheduler internal fixed priority, and frames are transmitted on the First Come First Serve principle.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Worst-case clock sync inaccuracy does not decrease link utilization, contrary to time-triggered approaches such as TAS (Qbv) and CQF (Qch).
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1Qca Path Control and Reservation (PCR) specifies extensions to the Intermediate Station to Intermediate Station (IS-IS) protocol to configure multiple paths in bridged networks.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The IEEE 802.1Qca standard uses Shortest Path Bridging (SPB) with a software-defined networking (SDN) hybrid mode - the IS-IS protocol handles basic functions, while the SDN controller manages explicit paths using Path Computation Elements (PCEs) at dedicated server nodes.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1Qca integrates control protocols to manage multiple topologies, configure an explicit forwarding path (a predefined path for each stream), reserve bandwidth, provides data protection and redundancy, and distribute flow synchronization and flow control messages.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] These are derived from Equal Cost Tree (ECT), Multiple Spanning Tree Instance (MSTI) and Internal Spanning Tree (IST), and Explicit Tree (ET) protocols.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1CB Frame Replication and Elimination for Reliability (FRER) sends duplicate copies of each frame over multiple disjoint paths to provide proactive seamless redundancy for control applications that cannot tolerate packet losses.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The packet replication can use traffic class and path information to minimize network congestion.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Each replicated frame has a sequence identification number, used to re-order and merge frames and to discard duplicates.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] FRER requires centralized configuration management and needs to be used with 802.1Qcc and 802.1Qca.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Industrial fault-tolerance HSR and PRP specified in IEC 62439-3 are supported.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] MRP state data for a stream takes 1500 bytes.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] With additional traffic streams and larger networks, the size of the database proportionally increases and MRP updates between bridge neighbors significantly slow down.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The Link-Local Registration Protocol (LRP) is optimized for a larger database size of about 1 Mbyte with efficient replication that allows incremental updates.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Unresponsive nodes with stale data are automatically discarded.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] While MRP is application specific, with each registered application defining its own set of operations, LRP is application neutral.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE P802.1Qdd project updates the distributed configuration model by defining new peer-to-peer Resource Allocation Protocol signaling built upon P802.1CS Link-local Registration Protocol.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] RAP will improve scalability and provide dynamic reservation for a larger number of streams with support for redundant transmission over multiple paths in 802.1CB FRER, and autoconfiguration of sequence recovery.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] RAP supports the 'topology-independent per-hop latency calculation' capability of TSN shapers such as 802.1Qch Cyclic Queuing and Forwarding (CQF) and P802.1Qcr Asynchronous Traffic Shaping (ATS).
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] It will also improve performance under high load and support proxying and enhanced diagnostics, all while maintaining backward compatibility and interoperability with MSRP.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE P802.1ABdh Station and Media Access Control Connectivity Discovery - Support for Multiframe Protocol Data Units (LLDPv2) updates LLDP to support IETF Link State Vector Routing protocol and improve efficiency of protocol messages.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] YANG is a Unified Modeling Language (UML) for configuration and state data, notifications, and remote procedure calls, to set up device configuration with network management protocols such as NETCONF/RESTCONF.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The IETF Deterministic Networking (DetNet) Working Group is focusing on defining deterministic data paths with high reliability and bounds on latency, loss, and packet delay variation (jitter), such as audio and video streaming, industrial automation, and vehicle control.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The goals of Deterministic Networking are to migrate time-critical, high-reliability industrial and audio-video applications from special-purpose Fieldbus networks to IP packet networks.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] To achieve these goals, DetNet uses resource allocation to manage buffer sizes and transmission rates in order to satisfy end-to-end latency requirements.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Service protection against failures with redundancy over multiple paths and explicit routes to reduce packet loss and reordering.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] The same physical network shall handle both time-critical reserved traffic and regular best-effort traffic, and unused reserved bandwidth shall be released for best-effort traffic.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] DetNet operates at the IP Layer 3 routed segments using a software-defined networking layer to provide IntServ and DiffServ integration, and delivers services over lower Layer 2 bridged segments using technologies such as MPLS and IEEE 802.1 AVB/TSN.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] Also, the protocol interworking defined by IEEE 802.1CB is used to advertise TSN sub-network capabilities to DetNet flows via the Active Destination MAC and VLAN Stream identification functions.
[src:audio-video-bridging/time-sensitive-networking] DetNet flows are matched by destination MAC address, VLAN ID and priority parameters to Stream ID and QoS requirements for talkers and listeners in the AVB/TSN sub-network.
